POSITION
IN DOCUMENT WHERE ELEMENT IS POSITIONED AND ITS FIXED PLACES 
1 static 
every html element is default as static do it prevent from any top effect 
position:static;
top:100px;
left:100px;


2 relative
The element stays in the normal flow, but you can move it relative to its original position.
The space it originally occupied remains.
position:relative;
top:20%;
bottom:30%;


3 absolute
The element is removed from normal flow.
It positions relative to the nearest positioned parent (parent with relative, absolute, or fixed).



l developer tip:
Most layouts use this combination:

position: relative → on parent
position: absolute → on child

This helps place elements inside containers easily.
by using relative as parent element and absolute as child element it will make it more responsive.
Why This Helps in Responsive Design

When the parent resizes on different screens:

The absolute element stays positioned relative to that parent
It doesn't break the layout


4 fixed 
the element is fixed relative to the viewport (screen).
It does not move when scrolling.

5 sticky 
Works like relative at first, then becomes fixed when scrolling


